<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-081-192  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 081 192.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Feb 1989 v29 n2 p27(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Implementing computer-aided learning in a university environment:some practical advice to a CAL agency.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leiblum, Mark David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The use of computer-aided learning (CAL) in colleges anduniversities is becoming widespread.andP;  A central CAL agency isrecommended for various reasons, among them: creation of a sharedpool of experts is more economical, development of coursework willbe faster, duplication of efforts will be avoided, costs ofmaterials acquisition will be lower, training of staff and facultycan be coordinated, general library and documentation resourcescan be efficiently maintained, and evaluation of coursework can beproperly done.andP;  However, for a central CAL agency to be effectiveit must provide a supply of demonstration programs on a wide rangeof subjects, update facilities and library resources and developcoursework which must be perceived by users as integral to thelearning process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Assisted InstructionColleges and UniversitiesEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>